    "script": [
        {
        "_id":"scr_title",
        "text":"The Goiânia Accident",
        "voice_start_time":0,
        "post_pause_duration":2
        },
        {
        "_id": "scr_intro",
        "text": "Chapter 1: A Fateful Discovery",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_intro_content",
        "text": "In September 1987, the Brazilian city of Goiânia became the site of one of the worst radiological incidents in history.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 0.5
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_abandoned_institute",
        "text": "It all began at an abandoned radiotherapy institute, where a dangerous source of radiation was left behind.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 0.5
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_cesium_capsule",
        "text": "Inside the abandoned building was a lead cylinder containing 1,375 curies of highly radioactive cesium-137.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_scavengers_title",
        "text": "Chapter 2: The Scavengers' Discovery",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_scavengers",
        "text": "Two scrap metal scavengers entered the site and took the heavy lead cylinder, thinking it might be valuable.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 0.5
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_discovery",
        "text": "At home, they managed to open the lead cylinder and discovered a mysterious glowing blue powder inside.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_contamination_title",
        "text": "Chapter 3: The Spread of Contamination",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_contamination",
        "text": "Fascinated by its blue glow, they showed it to friends and family. Some even took it home as a curiosity.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 0.5
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_symptoms",
        "text": "Within days, people began experiencing symptoms of acute radiation sickness, including nausea, vomiting, and skin burns.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_response_title",
        "text": "Chapter 4: The Emergency Response",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_response",
        "text": "Once authorities were alerted, a massive decontamination effort began. Over 100,000 people were monitored for radiation exposure.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_aftermath_title",
        "text": "Chapter 5: The Aftermath",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_aftermath",
        "text": "In the end, 4 people died, 249 were contaminated, and 112,000 were monitored. The Goiânia accident remains a stark reminder of the dangers of radioactive materials.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 2
      },
      {
        "_id": "scr_conclusion",
        "text": "This tragic incident serves as a powerful lesson on the importance of proper handling and disposal of radioactive materials, and the need for public awareness about radiation safety.",
        "voice_start_time": 0,
        "post_pause_duration": 1
      }
    ],
